response:
Let $\angle APB = \angle BPC = \angle CPA = \theta$. Then by the Law of Cosines, we have
\begin{align*}
PC^2 &= PB^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot PB \cdot BC \cdot \cos \theta \\
&= 6^2 + (21\sqrt{3})^2 - 2 \cdot 6 \cdot 21\sqrt{3} \cdot \cos \theta \\
&= 36 + 1323 - 252\sqrt{3} \cos \theta.
\end{align*}
Since $\triangle ABC$ is right-angled at $B$, $BC = \sqrt{AC^2 - AB^2} = \sqrt{AC^2 - 10^2}$.
 <deepthink>Now, since $P$ is the circumcenter of $\triangle ABC$, we know that $PA = PB = PC$. Therefore, $AC = 20$. Plugging this into our expression for $BC$, we get
\begin{align*}
BC &= \sqrt{AC^2 - 10^2} \\
&= \sqrt{20^2 - 10^2} \\
&= 10\sqrt{3}.
\end{align*}
 <answer>Now we can plug this into our expression for $PC^2$ to get
\begin{align*}
PC^2 &= 36 + 1323 - 252\sqrt{3} \cos \theta \\
&= 1359 - 252\sqrt{3} \cos \theta.
\end{align*}
We also have
\begin{align*}
PB^2 + PC^2 &= PA^2 \\
\Longleftrightarrow 6^2 + 1359 - 252\sqrt{3} \cos \theta &= 10^2 \\
\Longleftrightarrow 252\sqrt{3} \cos \theta &= 135.
\end{align*}
Therefore, $\cos \theta = \frac{135}{252\sqrt{3}} = \frac{5}{12}$. Plugging this into our expression for $PC^2$, we get
\begin{align*}
PC^2 &= 1359 - 252\sqrt{3} \cos \theta \\
&= 1359 - 252\sqrt{3} \cdot \frac{5}{12} \\
&= 1359 - 125\sqrt{3} \\
&= 1051.
\end{align*}
Therefore, $PC = \boxed{\sqrt{1051}}$.
</answer>

